'''Uwato Shrine''' (うわとじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945}} located in {{ill|lt=Gifu Prefecture|Q131277|WD=Q131277}}, {{ill|lt=Anpachi District|Q1204320|WD=Q1204320}}, {{ill|lt=Gōdo Town|Q1203575|WD=Q1203575}}.

It is a candidate shrine (ronsha) for Uwato Shrine of Anpachi District, Mino Province, listed in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Engishiki}}. (Another candidate shrine is {{ill|lt=Uwato Shrine (Anpachi Town)|Q11449527|WD=Q11449527|lt=Uwato Shrine}} “Ubatō-jinja” in {{ill|lt=Anpachi Town|Q474384|WD=Q474384}}, Anpachi District.) Under the {{ill|lt=modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=former shrine ranking system}}, it was classified as a gōsha.

=== History and overview ===
*The date of establishment is unknown. During the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963}}, it was known as Omon Daimyōjin and Okado Daimyōjin.
*Amid the turmoil of the {{ill|lt=Meiji Restoration|Q8707|WD=Q8707}} in the early {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Meiji period|1=UNKNOWN|WD=Q3125096}}, the shrine fell into ruin; the shrine buildings also deteriorated around this time, and today only a simple main sanctuary and worship hall remain.
*It is said that the shrine is currently managed by {{ill|lt=Hiyoshi Shrine (Gōdo Town)|Q11505069|WD=Q11505069|lt=Hiyoshi Shrine}}. According to one theory, in order to protect the sacred object during the chaos of the early Meiji period, the sacred object of Uwato Shrine was transferred to Hiyoshi Shrine.

=== Transportation ===
*About a 15-minute walk from {{ill|lt=Yōrō Railway|Q11666892|WD=Q11666892}} {{ill|lt=Hiro-Gōdo Station|Q5769897|WD=Q5769897}}.

